Elevator pitch

Background

_The clean air act of 1970 was the beginning of the end for the use of asbestos in home building. By 1976, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) was given authority to restrict the use of asbestos in paint. Homes built during and before this period are known to have materials with asbestos YOu can read more about this ban.

The state of Colorado has a large portion of their residential dwelling data that is missing the year built and they would like you to build a predictive model that can classify if a house is built pre 1980.

Colorado gave you home sales data for the city of Denver from 2013 on which to train your model. They said all the column names should be descriptive enough for your modeling and that they would like you to use the latest machine learning methods._

Show the code 
df_denver = pd.merge(d_ml, d_neighborhood, on="parcel")
Show the code 
# Separate the features (X) and targets (Y)
x = df_denver.filter(["livearea","basement","stories", "nbhd_2", "nbhd_625", "nbhd_526", "nbhd_101", "nocars", "status_I", "condition_AVG", 
"gartype_None", "arcstyle_END UNIT", "arcstyle_MIDDLE UNIT", "arcstyle_ONE AND HALF-STORY"])
y = df_denver[["before1980"]]

#%% Split the data into train and test sets
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = None)

MEANINGFUL QUESTION 2

Build a classification model labeling houses as being built âbefore 1980â or âduring or after 1980â. Your goal is to reach or exceed 90% accuracy. Explain your final model choice (algorithm, tuning parameters, etc) and describe what other models you tried.

I got an Accuracy of 0.9127428775777804. This means that the ml program can predict if a house was built before 1980 in a 91.27% of the times. I tried basically every column in the denverlm data set as proof and error and then was visualizing which ones would make my accuracy higher or lower. Then with the table of feature importance I discarted the features with lower importance. Then to make it more accurate I combined the data set of neighbohoods with the ml one. The hardest part that took me a long time was to figure it out what neighborhoods had houses before 1980 and count them. And then to know what are the biggest neighborhoods so that would help my model.

Show the code 
#%% Build and evaluate a decision tree
##Analizing R-squared
# Create a decision tree
classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth = 20)

# Fit the decision tree
classifier.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Test the decision tree (make predictions)
y_predicted = classifier.predict(x_test)

# Evaluate the decision tree
print("Accuracy:", metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_predicted))
